<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Characteristic Species</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Heterotheca</i> <i>oregona</i> or <i>Heterotheca</i> <i>sessiliflora</i> is dominant or co-dominant in the herbaceous layer with <i>Avena</i> <i>barbata</i>, <i>Brassica</i> <i>nigra</i>, <i>Bromus</i> <i>diandrus</i>, <i>Bromus</i> <i>hordeaceus</i>, <i>Clarkia</i> <i>purpurea</i>, <i>Croton</i> <i>setigerus</i>, <i>Erodium</i> spp., <i>Hypochaeris</i> <i>glabra</i>, <i>Lotus</i> <i>unifoliolatus</i> or <i>Vulpia</i> <i>myuros</i>. </div>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Vegetation Layers</h4>
	<div class="text">  Herbs < 1 m; cover is sparse to intermittent. </div>
</div>

        
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Membership Rules</h4>
	<ul class="text">
		
		<li><i>Heterotheca oregona</i> or <i>H. sessiliflora</i> > 30% relative cover in the herbaceous layer (Klein et al. 2015, Buck-Diaz et al. 2012).</li>
		
		<li><i>Heterotheca sessiliflora</i> > 50% relative cover, typically co-dominant with <i>Bromus hordeaceus</i>, in the herbaceous layer (Kittel et al. 2012).</li>
		
	</ul>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Habitats</h4>
	<div class="text"> Sandy and cobbled gravel bars in floodplains, along riparian terraces and stream banks, flats or slopes adjacent to riparian areas, dunes and headlands near the coast, and other seasonally disturbed areas.  </div>
</div>

        
