<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Heterotheca oregona</i> and <i>H. sessiliflora</i> are perennial herbs in the sunflower family that act like short-lived shrubs. They are generally between 2-10 dm tall. Plants can be bristly and/or glandular and produce many flower heads. <i>H. oregona</i> produces only discoid heads while <i>H. sessiliflora</i>  produces heads with ray and disk flowers.<br/>
<br/>
<i>Heterotheca oregona</i> occurs from British Columbia to California. It is found in low-elevation mountain forests and chaparral, often near water or seasonally dry streambeds. There are four varieties found in California that can be somewhat indistinct from one another.<br/>
<br/>
<i>Heterotheca sessiliflora</i> is native to California and Baja California and Sonora, Mexico. It is quite variable in appearance and its four subspecies may merge where ranges overlap. It is found at low elevations near the coast on beaches, dunes, headlands, headland, and coastal slopes. It can also be found further inland at low to moderate elevations in creek banks, grasslands, scrub, woodlands, and disturbed sites. <br/>
<br/>
This alliance occurs on sandy and cobbled gravel bars in floodplains, along riparian terraces and stream banks, moist flats or slopes adjacent to riparian areas, and other seasonally disturbed areas. Stands dominated by <i>H. oregona</i>  have been identified within the northern Great Valley and North Coast Ranges (Buck Diaz et al. 2012, Klein et al. 2015), while stands in the Central Coast Ranges include <i>H. sessiliflora</i> as the dominant (Kittel et al. 2012). Further sampling and analysis are needed across the state to determine other associations and relationships to related alliances. </div>
</div>

    
	
	
