    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        
            <p><i>Heterotheca </i>spp. occur widely across the state. More sampling is needed as the species have been collected along banks of rivers, creeks, and adjacent canyon slopes (UCB 2017) in many sections, including the Southern California Mountains and Valleys (M262B), Southern California Coast (261B) and otherwise.</p>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Central California Coast Ranges</b> (M262Af). Stands of <i>Heterotheca sessiliflora</i> ssp. <i>echinoides </i>often occur on creek banks and sometimes on disturbed flats to steep slopes in Pinnacles National Monument (Kittel et al. 2012). However, stands in other subsections need documentation.</li>
        
            <li><b>Great Valley</b> (262Aa, Af-h, Ao). Stands occur on flat to moderately steep slopes in upland and riparian settings (Buck-Diaz et al. 2012). Stands are mapped along the Sacramento River, Feather River, American River, and Cache Creek (VegCAMP and GIC 2013).</li>
        
            <li><b>Northern California Coast</b> (263Ag). Stands occur on riparian gravel and sand bars along rivers and creeks (Klein et al. 2015).</li>
        
            <li><b>Northern California Coast Ranges</b> (M261Bb). Stands occur on upper gravel bars in openings between <i> Salix exigua </i>stands or riparian tree stands such as along the Russian River and Dry Creek in Sonoma County (Klein et al. 2015).</li>
        
            <li><b>Northern California Interior Coast Ranges</b> (M261Cb). Stands of <i>Heterotheca oregona </i>are mapped on sandy and cobble gravel bars along the banks of the Sacramento River (VegCAMP and GIC 2013).</li>
        
            <li><b>Sierra Nevada Foothills</b> (M261Fc-e). Stands occur along the Kern River and Deer Creek in the southeastern Sierra Nevada Foothills and in Fort Tejon State Historic Park in the southern Sierra Nevada Foothills.</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Heterotheca oregona </i>and <i>H. sessiliflora </i>occur in riparian and coastal areas throughout California that may have been impacted by development, invasive species, grazing, etc.  Annual invasive plant species present a significant impact to <i>Heterotheca (oregona, sessiliflora)</i> stands and the removal of annual plants at the landscape scale greatly enhances the populations of  <i>Heterotheca</i> spp. (McGraw 2004a).  Because these species tend to occur in or near the edge of floodplains, these stands can also be impacted by altered flood regimes.
 
<i>Heterotheca (oregona, sessiliflora)</i> stands provide habitat for many organisms, including rare and endangered species. For instance, in the Santa Cruz Mountains, <i>H. sessiliflora </i>provides food for the Zayante band-winged grasshopper, a rare insect. <i>H. sessiliflora </i>makes up a good portion of this grasshopper's diet (McGraw 2004b). Also, the Lesser Nighthawk was found to be nesting in several stands of <i>Heterotheca (oregona, sessiliflora) </i>in the Great Valley ecoregion. </div>
</div>

    

    

